            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Leo Karam\u2019s life is measured in the rhythmic shudder of a city bus and the steady chime of stop requests. For 22 years, he has been a Muni operator, a constant presence in a city of perpetual change. Raised in the fog-dusted streets of the Excelsior District, Leo is the son of hardworking Filipino immigrants. His father was a cook, his mother a caregiver, and their home buzzed with the sounds of Tagalog and the scent of adobo. They preached the gospel of stability, a value Leo absorbed deeply.\n\nHis own path was supposed to include college, a vague plan to study business. That dream dissolved during his senior year of high school when his father suffered a debilitating stroke. Suddenly the family\u2019s rock, Leo shelved his ambitions and took a job stocking shelves at a grocery store to help with the bills. For years, he drifted between similar low-wage jobs until an uncle, a city mechanic, suggested he apply to Muni. The promise of a union job, good pay, and a pension was the stability his parents had always championed. He passed the exam and, at 22, began his career behind the wheel.\n\nThe job became his identity. From the elevated driver's seat of the 38-Geary or the 1-California, he watched San Francisco evolve. He saw tech booms fill his bus with lanyard-wearing millennials and witnessed the city\u2019s heartaches play out in the faces of his most vulnerable passengers. A long-term relationship ended a decade ago, strained by his odd hours and the quiet emotional toll of the job.\n\nNow, at 44, Leo lives a life of disciplined routine in a rent-controlled one-bedroom in the Inner Richmond. He takes the 5-Fulton to the Presidio Yard, a 2.1-mile commute to begin his workday. He is a quiet observer, known by sight to hundreds of daily commuters who never know his name. His aspirations are modest: to see his pension through to retirement, perhaps buy a small condo in Pacifica where the air is clean, and finally take the trip to the Philippines his mother always talks about. Leo Karam never built a startup or wrote a novel, but he has been an essential, moving part of San Francisco's soul, carrying its people toward their own destinations, one stop at a time."
