            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was 21, sitting in his parent's Excelsior kitchen, the air thick with the smell of liniment for his father. His uncle, the city mechanic, slid the Muni application across the table. It wasn\u2019t a thrilling opportunity; it was a lifeboat. The heavy paper felt like a final, binding choice. In that moment, the hazy dream of college dissolved completely, replaced by the concrete promise of a pension. It was the first decision he ever made that wasn't for himself, a quiet sacrifice that would come to define the steel in his spine.\n\n2.\nA few years into the job, driving a late-night 38-Geary, a young woman sat alone near the front, sobbing silently into her hands. Leo didn\u2019t say a word. He just drove smoother, eased into the stops, and made the turns wider, trying to give her the steadiest ride possible. When she pulled the cord, he waited until she was well onto the curb before closing the doors. It was then he understood his job wasn't just to move people, but to shepherd their private heartaches safely through the darkness.\n\n3.\nThe clearest memory of the end with Sarah wasn\u2019t a fight, but a quiet dinner. She was telling him about her day, her face full of life, and he realized he was only half-listening. His mind was still on the route, replaying a near-miss with a bike messenger and the face of an angry passenger. He saw the light in her eyes fade as she understood he wasn't really there with her. The job had taken up a space inside him that was supposed to have been for her, leaving him isolated even when seated across the table.\n\n4.\nHis mother rode his bus for the first time when he was 23. She sat right behind him on the 1-California, holding a paper bag that smelled of garlic rice and adobo\u2014his *baon*. At a red light on Sacramento Street, she leaned forward and whispered in Tagalog, \"You look so official, *anak*.\" A wave of pride washed over him, solid and real. He wasn't just a driver; he was the stability his family needed, a son keeping his promise in a uniform his mother could see and be proud of.\n\n5.\nJust last year, a young tech worker, headphones on and eyes glued to his phone, looked up and saw an elderly *Lola* struggling with her grocery bags. Without hesitation, he stood up and offered his seat. The woman beamed, thanking him profusely. Leo watched it all in his wide mirror, a silent, knowing observer. The city's skyline changed, the faces on his bus changed, but these small acts of grace were constants. They were the city\u2019s true heartbeat, a rhythm he had the honor of carrying every single day."
